What are Microbial Fermentation APIs and Why is Demand Increasing?
Microbial fermentation APIs are biologically derived active pharmaceutical ingredients produced through controlled fermentation processes using microorganisms such as bacteria, fungi, actinomycetes, and yeast. During fermentation, microorganisms convert inexpensive carbon and nitrogen sources including glucose, starch, sucrose, soybean flour, cotton-seed flour, and peptone into valuable pharmaceutical compounds including antibiotics, amino acids, vitamins, hormones, organic acids, nucleotides, and biological products.

Compared with conventional chemical synthesis, microbial fermentation enables efficient production of complex molecules with excellent purity, scalability, and sustainability. Advances in metabolic engineering, strain optimization, bioprocess automation, and downstream purification technologies continue improving production efficiency while reducing manufacturing costs, making microbial fermentation indispensable for modern pharmaceutical manufacturing.

